title.narrative: CBSI-ESC-ESF-Community, Family, and Youth Resilience (CFYR) Program

description.narrative: (State Western Hemisphere Regional): The Eastern and Southern Caribbean (ESC) has suffered from growing levels of youth crime and violence, with five countries ranking in the top-twenty worldwide for the number of homicides per capita. Youth crime and violence prevention will improve by reducing risk factors and increasing resilience factors strengthened within targeted communities where high rates of crime and violence occur. USAID's community-level violence prevention activity will continue to focus resources on three countries with among the highesT crime and violence problems (St. Lucia, St. Kitts and Nevis, and Guyana) and further concentrate programming in five crime hot-spot communities within each of these three countries. The program seeks to reduce risk factors and increase resilience factors for youth aged 10 to 29 through interventions with families, communities, non-government entities, service providers, and government agencies. By training youth and community workers (eg. social workers and probation officers) to understand and address violence in their communities, the program promotes ownership and oversight. The activity also addresses the needs of youth at an individual level, providing vocational and life skills training through after-school and summer camp programming, as well as counseling and psycho-social services for youth who have exhibited risk factors that make them most vulnerable to violence. USAID will continue to use data to match at-risk youth with interventions, including work opportunities, and help community stakeholders identify and implement solutions to create an environment for positive youth development. The project will continue its efforts to systematically advance sustainability by building local capacity to manage the counseling and workforce development programs after USAID funding ends. At the end of the project, key tools, methodologies and approaches will be transferred to targeted government and local partner
